Question: How to use the Firebase RecyclerView with a specific layout:
I'm trying to use Firebase RecyclerView with a specific layout but I can't seem to get it to work. I have followed the guide on the Firebase website but I'm still getting an error.
I have a layout file named "item_layout.xml" and I'm trying to use it in my RecyclerView. Here is my code:
public class MyAdapter extends FirebaseRecyclerAdapter<Item, MyAdapter.MyViewHolder> {

    public MyAdapter(FirebaseRecyclerOptions<Item> options) {
        super(options);
    }

    @Override
    protected void onBindViewHolder(@NonNull MyViewHolder holder, int position, @NonNull Item model) {
        holder.textView.setText(model.getName());
    }

    @NonNull
    @Override
    public MyViewHolder onCreateViewHolder(@NonNull ViewGroup parent, int viewType) {
        View view = LayoutInflater.from(parent.getContext()).inflate(R.layout.item_layout, parent, false);
        return new MyViewHolder(view);
    }

    static class MyViewHolder extends RecyclerView.ViewHolder {
        TextView textView;

        MyViewHolder(View itemView) {
            super(itemView);
            textView = itemView.findViewById(R.id.textView);
        }
    }
}

And here is my Item class:
public class Item {
    private String name;

    public Item() {
        // Default constructor required for calls to DataSnapshot.getValue(Item.class)
    }

    public Item(String name) {
        this.name = name;
    }

    public String getName() {
        return name;
    }

    public void setName(String name) {
        this.name = name;
    }
}

The error I'm getting is:

java.lang.NullPointerException: Attempt to invoke virtual method 'void android.widget.TextView.setText(java.lang.CharSequence)' on a null object reference

I'm guessing that the error is because I'm not correctly inflating the layout file in the onCreateViewHolder method. I've tried changing the layout file name and the TextView id in the MyViewHolder class but I'm still getting the same error.

A: The error is because you are trying to set the text of a TextView that is not initialized.
In your onCreateViewHolder method, you are inflating the layout but you are not returning the ViewHolder.
You should return a new instance of MyViewHolder(view) at the end of the onCreateViewHolder method.
Here is the corrected code:
@NonNull
@Override
public MyViewHolder onCreateViewHolder(@NonNull ViewGroup parent, int viewType) {
    View view = LayoutInflater.from(parent.getContext()).inflate(R.layout.item_layout, parent, false);
    return new MyViewHolder(view);
}

This should solve your problem.

